# Module Grants and Permission Guide

Use this when working with module grants and `BasePermissionService`.

## Core Rules

- Keep grants in `<module>.grants.ts`.
- Keep authorization checks in `<module>.service.ts`.
- Action names in `accessGuard`/`accessGuardAsync` must exactly match action names defined in grants.
- Prefer canonical action vocabulary: `read`, `write`, `delete`, `publish`.

## Default Grants from `@m5kdev/backend`

Backend modules ship default grants via `<module>.grants.ts`. These provide sensible role/access defaults so apps work out of the box.

### Auth Module (`defaultAuthGrants`)

```typescript
import { flattenNestedGrants } from "@m5kdev/backend/modules/base/base.grants";

export const defaultAuthGrants = flattenNestedGrants({
  auth: {
    user: {
      admin: { read: "all", write: "all", delete: "all" },
      user:  { read: "own", write: "own", delete: "own" },
    },
    organization: {
      owner:  { read: "all", write: "all", delete: "all" },
      admin:  { read: "all", write: "all" },
      member: { read: "own" },
    },
  },
});
```

### Grant Structure

`flattenNestedGrants` accepts a `NestedGrants` object shaped as:

```
{ [resource]: { [level]: { [role]: { [action]: Access } } } }
```

- **resource** — domain area (e.g. `"auth"`).
- **level** — scope: `"user"`, `"team"`, or `"organization"`.
- **role** — role name at that level (e.g. `"admin"`, `"member"`, `"owner"`).
- **action** — canonical action (`"read"`, `"write"`, `"delete"`, `"publish"`).
- **Access** — `"all"` (any entity) or `"own"` (ownership check required).

The function flattens this into a `Grant[]` consumed by `BasePermissionService`.

### Overriding Default Grants

Backend modules accept optional grants via their constructor, falling back to the shipped defaults:

```typescript
class AuthModule extends BaseModule<...> {
  private readonly grants: Grant[];

  constructor(grants?: Grant[]) {
    super();
    this.grants = grants ?? defaultAuthGrants;
  }
}
```

Apps can override grants at composition time:

```typescript
// apps/myapp/server/src/modules.ts
const authModule = new AuthModule(
  flattenNestedGrants({
    auth: {
      user: {
        admin: { read: "all", write: "all", delete: "all" },
        user:  { read: "own", write: "own" }, // no self-delete
      },
      organization: {
        owner:  { read: "all", write: "all", delete: "all" },
        admin:  { read: "all", write: "all" },
        member: { read: "own" },
      },
    },
  })
);
```

Only override when the app needs to deviate from the defaults. Pass `undefined` (or omit) to keep default behavior.

### Writing Default Grants for New Backend Modules

When adding a new module to `@m5kdev/backend`:

1. Create `<module>.grants.ts` in the module directory.
2. Export a `default<Module>Grants` constant using `flattenNestedGrants`.
3. Accept optional `Grant[]` in the module constructor, falling back to the default.
4. Pass the grants to `BasePermissionService` via the service constructor.

## Recommended Pattern

Define typed actions once and reuse in both grants and service:

```typescript
export const contentActions = ["read", "write", "delete", "publish"] as const;
export type ContentAction = (typeof contentActions)[number];
```

Use these actions in grants and in service guard calls to avoid string drift.

## Service Choice

- Use `BasePermissionService` only if the module actually performs permission checks.
- If a module has no `accessGuard*` usage, use `BaseService` instead.

## Guard Placement

- Guard read/update/delete/publish operations at service boundaries.
- Keep repository methods permission-agnostic.

## Anti-Patterns

- Grant declares `write` while service checks `update`.
- Decorating a module with grants but never enforcing them in service methods.
- Doing permission checks in tRPC/router instead of service.
- Duplicating default grants in app code instead of relying on the backend defaults.
- Overriding grants without understanding the full default set (always check `<module>.grants.ts` first).
